# Laravel Games Development Rules

## Project Context
This is a progressive game development challenge testing Laravel skills through building increasingly complex games. Focus on clean, reusable, testable code that scales across multiple games.

## Architecture Patterns

### Game Development
- All games MUST implement `App\Games\Contracts\GameInterface`
- Game logic goes in separate Engine classes (pure functions)
- Livewire components handle UI state only
- Register games in `AppServiceProvider`
- Follow existing naming conventions: `{GameName}Game.php`, `{GameName}Engine.php`

### Directory Structure
```
app/Games/{GameName}/
├── {GameName}Game.php      # GameInterface implementation
├── {GameName}Engine.php    # Game logic (pure functions)
└── AI/{GameName}AI.php     # AI opponents (when needed)
```

### Testing Requirements
- ALWAYS create both Unit and Feature tests for new games
- Unit tests: `tests/Unit/Games/{GameName}/`
- Feature tests: `tests/Feature/Games/{GameName}/`
- Test game logic, UI interactions, and score tracking
- Use descriptive test names: `it_can_detect_winning_condition`

### Frontend Patterns
- Use Livewire Volt for reactive components
- Component files: `resources/views/livewire/games/{slug}.blade.php`
- State management via Livewire properties
- Leverage existing SVG assets in `resources/img/`
- Follow Tailwind classes for consistency
- Maintain dark/light mode compatibility

## Code Quality Standards

### PHP Standards
- Type hints on all method parameters and returns
- DocBlocks for complex methods and arrays
- PSR-12 coding standards
- Use Laravel Pint for formatting

### Game State Management
- Game states as associative arrays with typed keys
- Immutable state transitions (return new state)
- Validate moves before applying
- Handle edge cases gracefully

### Error Handling
- Graceful degradation for invalid moves
- Clear error messages for users
- Log unexpected errors
- Fail-safe defaults

## Reusability Focus

### Shared Components
- Extract common UI patterns into Blade components
- Create reusable game utilities in `app/Games/Shared/`
- Share testing helpers across games
- Build composable scoring systems

### Performance
- Minimize database queries (scores only)
- Use efficient algorithms for game logic
- Cache when beneficial, avoid over-caching
- Consider memory usage for large game states

## Documentation Requirements

### Code Documentation
- Update ARCHITECTURE.md for new patterns
- Document complex algorithms inline
- Maintain clear README sections for each game
- Use conventional commits for changes

### Self-Documentation
- Use descriptive variable and method names
- Extract magic numbers into named constants
- Comment WHY, not WHAT
- Keep functions focused and single-purpose

## Testing Philosophy

### Test-Driven Development
- Write failing tests first for new features
- Test edge cases and error conditions
- Aim for high coverage without testing trivial code
- Use factories for test data generation

### Test Organization
- Group related tests logically
- Use setup methods to reduce duplication
- Test one concept per test method
- Make tests readable as documentation

## AI Development (When Required)

### Algorithm Choice
- Use deterministic algorithms, not neural networks
- Implement difficulty levels through lookahead depth
- Minimax with alpha-beta pruning for strategy games
- Heuristic evaluation functions for complex games

### AI Integration
- AI moves follow same interface as human moves
- Configurable difficulty settings
- Optional hints/suggestions for players
- Fair play (no cheating through hidden information)

## Deployment Considerations

### Environment
- Laravel Herd for local development
- SQLite database for simplicity
- Assume PowerShell 7 environment
- Use `npm run dev` for asset watching

### Git Workflow
- Conventional commits with clear scopes
- Commit after completing each game
- Keep commits focused and atomic
- Tag major milestones

## Remember
- Build incrementally, test thoroughly
- Prioritize code reuse and maintainability
- Focus on user experience and clean UI
- Document decisions for future reference
- This is a marathon, not a sprint - pace accordingly
